'''Praskvica Monastery''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|<U+041C><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0440> <U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0430>}}) is a [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodox]] [[List of Serbian monasteries|monastery]] in <U+010C>elobrdo, a village in [[Budva]] municipality in modern-day [[Montenegro]]. It was spiritual and political center of [[Pa<U+0161>trovi<U+0107>i]]. The name of monastery is taken from the peach-scented water of the nearby spring (''praskva'', diminutive ''praskvica'' means little peach).<ref name="Tomas<U+0306>evi<U+0107>1982">{{cite book|author=Nebojs<U+0306>a Tomas<U+0306>evi<U+0107>|title=Treasures of Yugoslavia: an encyclopedic touring guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=zCIuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1982|publisher=Yugoslaviapublic}}</ref>

== Establishment ==

According to the some stories the monastery was founded in 1050 while it is recorded in the written documents in 1307.<ref name="D<U+017E>omi<U+0107>2006">{{cite book|author=Velibor V. D<U+017E>omi<U+0107>|title=Pravoslavlje u Crnoj Gori|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=leSQAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=12 June 2013|year=2006|publisher=Svetigora}}</ref> That document is a charter [[Stephen Uro<U+0161> II Milutin of Serbia]] issued during his visit to [[Kotor]] in which he confirms to the Church of the Holy Trinity the ownership over some villages granted to the church by his mother [[Helen of Anjou]].<ref name="Luketi<U+0107>1966">{{cite book|author=Miroslav Luketi<U+0107>|title=Budva, Sv: Stefan, Petrovac|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2YgNAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=15 June 2013|year=1966|publisher=Turisti<U+010D>ki savez|page=163}}</ref>

== Churches ==
Six churches belong to Praskvica Monastery.

Two churches are within the complex of this monastery. The older church is dedicated to the [[Holy Trinity (disambiguation)|Holy Trinity]] while the other, built by [[Bal<U+0161>a III]] and his mother [[Jelena Bal<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Jelena]]<ref name="Strika1930">{{cite book|author=Bo<U+0161>ko Strika|title=Srpske zaduzbine: Dalmatinski manastiri|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=nqSxAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=14 June 2013|year=1930|publisher=Tiskara "Merkantile"|page=264|quote=<U+0422><U+0443> <U+0458><U+0435> <U+0446><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0443> <U+0433><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+0435> 1413 <U+043F><U+043E><U+0434><U+043D><U+0433><U+0430><U+043E> <U+0411><U+0430><U+043B><U+0448><U+0430> III <U+0421><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0438><U+043C><U+0438><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+045B> <U+0411><U+0430><U+043B><U+0448><U+0438><U+045B> <U+0438> <U+045A><U+0435><U+0433><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430> <U+043C><U+0430><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0408><U+0435><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D><U+0430>, <U+043A><U+045B><U+0438> <U+043A><U+043E><U+0441><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433> <U+043C><U+0443><U+0447><U+0435><U+043F><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0421><U+0432>. <U+041B><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+0440><U+0430>}}</ref> in 1413, is dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Godi<U+0161>njica Nikole <U+010C>upi<U+0107>a|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=P9A4AQAAMAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1897|page=205}}</ref><ref name="Popovi<U+0107>1975">{{cite book|author=Justin Sp Popovi<U+0107>|title=<U+017D>itija svetih|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZNNZAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1975|publisher=Izdanje Manastire sv. <U+0106>elije kod Valjeva|page=463|quote=<U+043C><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0440> <U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0430> <U+0441><U+0430> <U+0446><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0430><U+043C><U+0430> <U+0421><U+0432>. <U+0422><U+0440><U+043E>j<U+0438><U+0446><U+0435> <U+0438> <U+0421><U+0432>. <U+041D><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E><U+043B><U+0435>,}}</ref> The church was built in the [[Ra<U+0161>ka architectural school]] style.<ref name="<U+0110>uri<U+0107>Babi<U+0107>-<U+0110>or<U+0111>evi<U+0107>1997">{{cite book|author1=Vojislav J. <U+0110>uri<U+0107>|author2=Gordana Babi<U+0107>-<U+0110>or<U+0111>evi<U+0107>|title=Srpska umetnost u srednjem veku: XIV-XVI vek|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=GyNMAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=15 June 2013|year=1997|publisher=Srpska knji<U+017E>evna zadruga|page=123|quote=<U+041C><U+0435><U+0452><U+0443><U+0442><U+0438><U+043C>, <U+043F><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438><U+0436><U+0443><U+045B><U+0438> 1413. <U+0433><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+0435> <U+0445><U+0440><U+0430><U+043C> <U+0421><U+0432>. <U+041D><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E><U+043B><U+0435> <U+0443> <U+043C><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0440><U+0443> <U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0438> <U+0443> <U+041F><U+0430><U+0448><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+045B><U+0438><U+043C><U+0430>, <U+0411><U+0430><U+043B><U+0448><U+0430> III <U+0458><U+0435> <U+0443><U+0447><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0435><U+043E><U+0431><U+0438><U+0447><U+0430><U+043D> <U+043F><U+043E><U+0434><U+0443><U+0445><U+0432><U+0430><U+0442>: <U+043E><U+0431><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430><U+043E> <U+0433><U+0430> <U+0458><U+0435> <U+0443><U+0433><U+043B><U+0435><U+0434><U+0430><U+0458><U+0443><U+045B><U+0438> <U+0441><U+0435> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0440><U+0430><U+0448><U+043A><U+043E> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0430><U+0434><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435><U+0459><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0438><U+0437> XIII <U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+0430>.}}</ref> In the same year a small house was built near the church.<ref name="Luketi<U+0107>1966">{{cite book|author=Miroslav Luketi<U+0107>|title=Budva, Sv: Stefan, Petrovac|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2YgNAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=14 June 2013|year=1966|publisher=Turisti<U+010D>ki savez|page=163|quote=<U+041E><U+043A><U+043E> <U+0446><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0435> <U+0458><U+0435> <U+0433><U+0440><U+043E><U+0431><U+0459><U+0435>. <U+0423><U+0437> <U+0441><U+0430><U+043C><U+0443> <U+0446><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0443> <U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+0430><U+0437><U+0438> <U+0441><U+0435> <U+043A><U+0443><U+045B><U+0430> <U+043A><U+043E><U+0458><U+0430> <U+0458><U+0435> <U+0441><U+0430><U+0433><U+0440><U+0430><U+0452><U+0435><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0443> <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E> <U+0434><U+043E><U+0431><U+0430> <U+043A><U+0430><U+0434><U+0430>...}}</ref> After the church was reconstructed in 1847 only a part of one wall of the original church building remained.<ref name="dru<U+0161>tvo1922">{{cite book|author=Srpsko geografsko dru<U+0161>tvo|title=Glasnik Srpskog geografskog dru<U+0161>tva: Bulletin de la Soci<U+00E9>t<U+00E9> serbe de geographie|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-Tv5fVh-s74C|accessdate=15 June 2013|year=1922|publisher=Srpsko geografsko dru<U+0161>tvo|page=216}}</ref>

There are four churches on [[Sveti Stefan]] that also belong to Praskvica Monastery. One of them was destroyed by the communists and turned into casino.<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+041C><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0440> <U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0430>|url=http://www.mitropolija.me/?page_id=1701|publisher=Metropolitanate of Montenegro and the Littoral|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref> Some of its icons were painted in 1681 by the painter whose name was Radul.<ref name="<U+041F><U+0435><U+0442><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+045B>1974">{{cite book|author=<U+0421><U+0440><U+0435><U+0442><U+0435><U+043D> <U+041F><U+0435><U+0442><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+045B>|title=Manastir Sveta Trojica kod Pljevalja|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=o40FAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1974|publisher=<U+0418><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0442><U+0443><U+0442> <U+0437><U+0430> <U+0418><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+0458><U+0443> <U+0423><U+043C><U+0435><U+0442><U+043D><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0424><U+0438><U+043B><U+043E><U+0437><U+043E><U+0444><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433> <U+0444><U+0430><U+043A><U+0443><U+043B><U+0442><U+0435><U+0442><U+0430>|page=64}}</ref> According to some stories, the cross of [[Emperor Du<U+0161>an]] is kept in this monastery.<ref name="Moskovljevi<U+0107>1972">{{cite book|author=Olga Moskovljevi<U+0107>|title=Svetlosti Mediterana|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=v-ExAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1972|publisher=Matica srpska|page=23}}</ref>

== Jegor Stroganov ==
There is a popular story about Jegor Stroganov, an one-armed Russian military officer who lived in Praskvica Monastery as a monk at the end of 18th and beginning of 19th century. According to this story he came to Praskvica at the end of 18th century and became a monk in Praskvica Monastery and pledged for silence.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.69.html:159107-Jegorov-put-ponovo-prohodan | title=Jegorov put ponovo prohodan | publisher=Novosti | date=22 June  2004 | accessdate=2013-06-15 | quote=Ovaj jedinstveni put od mora do sela <U+010C>elobrdo iznad Svetog Stefana, koji je u 19. veku izgradio Jegor Stroganov, koji je stigao u manastir Praskvica iz carske Rusije, po<U+0161>to se zavetovao <U+0107>utanjem....koji ga je gradio punih deset godina.}}</ref> At the beginning of 19th century he alone built 3 kilometer stone road from Sveti Stefan to the monastery after 10 years of building.<ref name="Luketi<U+0107>1966">{{cite book|author=Miroslav Luketi<U+0107>|title=Budva, Sv: Stefan, Petrovac|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2YgNAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=1966|publisher=Turisti<U+010D>ki savez|page=165|quote=<U+041F><U+0443><U+0442> <U+043E><U+0434> <U+043C><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0440><U+0430> <U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438><U+0446><U+0435> <U+0434><U+043E> <U+0414><U+0443><U+0459><U+0435><U+0432><U+0430> <U+0438> <U+0434><U+0430><U+0459><U+0435> <U+0434><U+043E> <U+041F><U+0430><U+0448><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432>- <U+0441><U+043A><U+0435> <U+0433><U+043E><U+0440><U+0435> <U+0438><U+0437><U+0440><U+0430><U+0434><U+0438><U+043E> <U+0458><U+0435> <U+043A><U+0440><U+0430><U+0458><U+0435><U+043C> XVIII <U+0438> <U+043F><U+043E><U+0447><U+0435><U+0442><U+043A><U+043E><U+043C> XIX <U+0432><U+0438>- <U+0458><U+0435><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0420><U+0443><U+0441> <U+0408><U+0435><U+0433><U+043E><U+0440> <U+0421><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0433><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>,}}</ref> This road has been named Jegor's road after Jegor Stroganov.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pravoslavlje|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=zoAPAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=13 June 2013|year=2007|publisher=Izdaje Srpska patrijar<U+0161>ija|page=120}}</ref> A drama titled "Jegor's road", written by Serbian playwright [[Vida Ognjenovi<U+0107>]], is inspired with the story about Jegor.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.pobjeda.me/arhiva/?datum=2004-06-20&id=33279 | title=Dozvalo je o<U+010D>evo <U+0107>utanje | publisher=Pobjeda | date=20 June 2004 | accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>

